# Chapter 1 — The City of Decaying Splendor (Peking, China)

*Keeper-facing summary of Chapter 1 of The Children of Fear. This condenses the
chapter's structure, beats, clues, and guidance for running it; the mechanical
stat blocks live in the sibling `.actor`, and the queryable scene/clue structure
in the sibling `.arc`. Consult your copy of the campaign for the full text,
read-aloud passages, and handouts.*

## Role in the campaign

Chapter 1 is the campaign's on-ramp. It gathers the investigators in Peking in
September 1923, hooks them into Langdon Warner's expedition to a rumored secret
cave at the Caves of the Thousand Buddhas (Tun-huang), and quietly introduces the
campaign's hidden antagonists — the Tokabhaya — who are already watching the
investigators and seeding them with cryptic visions. It ends with the party
setting out west along the old Silk Roads, launching the journey that structures
the rest of the campaign.

## Setting

Peking, capital of the young, warlord-riven Republic of China: a walled,
compartmentalized city (Chinese, Tartar, Imperial, and Forbidden cities, with the
foreign Legation Quarter to the east) of decaying imperial grandeur, expatriate
privilege, and street-level poverty. The chapter supplies period colour on
currency, weather, transport (electric trams; tens of thousands of rickshaws;
rare motorcars), local etiquette, and a short Peking timeline — background the
Keeper can lean on to make the city feel alive.

## Structure and key beats

**Set Up — An Educational Invitation.** On the evening of Thursday 20 September
1923 each investigator receives, by envelope, an invitation from the China
Lecture Association to a talk that night at Peking University (Examination Hall 5,
7:30 for 8:00 p.m., cocktail reception before and after). The speaker is
**Sofian Bazaz-Wain, photojournalist**, and his subject — *"A Long Road to
Travel: From Srinagar to Sian in the Footsteps of My Forebears"* — quietly
previews the campaign's own east-to-west route. A short, personal note from
**Prof. Wang Enlai** (Director of the American School of Archaeology) is enclosed.
Players are also handed **"What Your Investigator Knows 1: China and Peking"**
(Appendix C) — their characters' baseline knowledge of the setting. This is the
device that assembles the party.

**Start — The Lecture.** En route to the lecture the investigators feel watched.
At the venue, the concealed Tokabhaya agents psychically probe the audience; the
investigators (and a few other attendees) suffer *Visions in the Dark* — brief,
disorienting glimpses that include the Tun-huang caves. A **Hard POW** roll can
resist the intrusion; a **Psychology** roll afterward lets a character pick out
the other bewildered visionaries (a soft introduction of the party to one
another). The talk proceeds with period business (magic-lantern slides, a restive
student audience, cultural notes). Afterward, **Prof. Wang Enlai** — successor to
Langdon Warner at the American School of Archaeology — gathers the investigators
and shares a desperate telegram (handout) from Warner begging for a team to be
sent to Tun-huang. Wang recruits them, downplaying the need for special expertise
("a willingness to help Warner" suffices).

**Making Plans.** The next day the investigators feel spied upon; a sudden,
unnatural storm marks their trip out to Yenching University. In Wang's office he
provides a travel permit (a Chinese-language document; a Language roll parses it),
secures motor vehicles to carry them as far as Sian, hands over a purse of silver
dollars (short of what's needed — sponsors will reimburse), and briefs them on
Warner, the expedition, and Tun-huang. Key briefing facts: Warner is an authority
on Oriental art and Buddhist history and the school's founding director, now with
Harvard's Fogg Museum; the Tun-huang caves have been repeatedly stripped by
mostly Western archaeologists; growing Chinese resentment of that looting colours
the journey. Wang warns of road hazards (bandits, rogue soldiers, corrupt
officials, White Russian refugees, flash storms) and offers the university
library. From Sian onward the party must arrange their own porters, pack animals,
and carts — Wang points them to **Mi Han** in Sian (Chapter 2).

**On the Road.** The investigators depart Peking by enclosed coach with a shabby
military escort mustered at Tiananmen Square, and the westward journey toward the
Silk Roads begins.

## Travel by Map

The campaign's signature travel device: because distances are vast, the Keeper
"red-lines" the route (à la *Pulp Cthulhu* / adventure serials), tracing progress
on a map and dropping in provided *en-route* encounters to build a mounting sense
of strangeness and interference rather than resolving every mile in play.

## Key NPCs

- **Prof. Wang Enlai** — head of the American School of Archaeology; the
  investigators' patron and recruiter for this chapter. (Stat block in the `.actor`.)
- **Sofian Bazaz-Wain** — traveling academic and the evening's lecturer; offered
  as a possible pre-generated investigator, else an NPC who can advise on the
  route to Tun-huang.
- **Langdon Warner** — offstage in Chapter 1: the archaeologist whose urgent
  telegram is the hook. (His full stat block appears with Chapter 2's cast.)
- **The Tokabhaya** — hidden agents of the campaign's antagonist, already
  surveilling the investigators and responsible for the psychic visions; unseen
  here but the first thread of the overarching plot.
- **Chinese soldiers / driver** — the military escort and transport out of Peking.
  (Group stat blocks in the `.actor`.)

## Clues & handouts (as information)

- **The lecture invitation + note** — the summons that gathers the party.
- **Warner's telegram** — the desperate plea that frames the mission: assemble a
  team and get to Tun-huang with all speed to secure a secret cave before others do.
- **The visions in the dark** — a supernatural clue: the Tun-huang caves recur in
  the imposed visions, tying the mundane job to the Mythos undercurrent and
  signalling that outside forces already have an interest in the investigators.
- **Wang's travel permit** — the document that eases official passage on the road west.

## Keeper guidance

- Use the party-assembly at the lecture (the shared vision + Psychology recognition)
  to bind investigators who don't already know each other.
- Keep the Tokabhaya surveillance subtle — a sense of being watched, the unnatural
  storm — foreshadowing without exposure this early.
- Bazaz-Wain-as-PC is accommodated: the Keeper need not force that player to
  "give the lecture"; slides left with the technician cover it.

## Transition to Chapter 2

The chapter ends with the convoy rolling west. Chapter 2 (*To the Gates of the
Sun*) picks up the overland journey toward Chang'an (Sian) and on to Tun-huang,
where the party must hire their onward caravan (Mi Han) and reach Warner.
